### What version of Bun is running?

1.2.17+282dda62c

### What platform is your computer?

Linux 6.8.0-1026-oracle aarch64 aarch64

### What steps can reproduce the bug?

### Description

When bundling stylesheets with cascade layers that are declared without assigning styles, the bundler leaves the layer declarations and import statements at the bottom of the bundled stylesheet.

### Steps To Reproduce

1. Create the following files and their contents in the project root:

`index.html`:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en-US">
  <head>
    <title>Test</title>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="initial-scale=1, width=device-width">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="./main.css">
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Hello, Test.</h1>
  </body>
</html>
```

`a.css`:

```css
body {
  margin: 0;
}
```

`b.css`:

```css
h1 {
  font-family: sans-serif;
}
```

`c.css`:

```css
.text-centered {
  text-align: center;
}
```

`main.css`:

```css
@layer one;
@layer two;
@layer three;

/* OR declare the layers with the syntax on the next line, the same bug happens. */
/* @layer one, two, three; */

@import url('./a.css') layer(one);
@import url('./b.css) layer(two);
@import url('./c.css) layer(three);
```

2. Run `bun ./index.html` OR `bun build ./index.html --outdir=out` OR `bun build ./main.css --outdir=out`.

### What is the expected behavior?

The expected behavior is that the bundler doesn't leave the layer declarations and import statements at the bottom of the bundled stylesheet. Other than that, the bundled CSS is correct.

### What do you see instead?

Bundler output with cascade layers declared with separate `@layer` statements:

```css
/* a.css */
@layer one {
  body {
    margin: 0;
  }
}

/* b.css */
@layer two {
  h1 {
    font-family: sans-serif;
  }
}

/* c.css */
@layer three {
  .text-centered {
    text-align: center;
  }
}

/* main.css */
@layer one;
@layer two;
@layer three;
@import "./a.css" layer(one);
@import "./b.css" layer(two);
@import "./c.css" layer(three);
```

Output with multiple layers declared in one `@layer` statement:

```css
/* a.css */
@layer one {
  body {
    margin: 0;
  }
}

/* b.css */
@layer two {
  h1 {
    font-family: sans-serif;
  }
}

/* c.css */
@layer three {
  .text-centered {
    text-align: center;
  }
}

/* main.css */
@layer one, two, three;
@import "./a.css" layer(one);
@import "./b.css" layer(two);
@import "./c.css" layer(three);
```

### Additional information

- This bug was also present on Bun v1.2.16.
- Cascade layers that are defined with styles do bundle correctly, it's _only_ layers declared without styles that are affected.

oven-sh/bun#23991.body:
### What version of Bun is running?

1.3.0

### What platform is your computer?

Microsoft Windows NT 10.0.19045.0 x64

### What steps can reproduce the bug?

Have a MySQL database w/ a column of type `BINARY(16)`

Use Bun to query it.

### What is the expected behavior?

Get back a node `Buffer` of length 16

### What do you see instead?

A string.

### Additional information

I don't think this is explicitly documented but I assume `BINARY` falls under `BLOB`: https://bun.com/docs/runtime/sql#type-handling

This is different than how `mysql` and `mysql2` handle it, which is documented here: https://github.com/mysqljs/mysql#type-casting

Furthermore, they have more options for converting types such as `fieldCast`:

```js
connection = mysql.createConnection({
  typeCast: function (field, next) {
    if (field.type === 'TINY' && field.length === 1) {
      return (field.string() === '1'); // 1 = true, 0 = false
    } else {
      return next();
    }
  }
});
```

Strings are just a pain to deal with in my app. I stored it as binary because I want it as binary.

This is bad enough that I think Bun should change the default from string to Buffer, but failing that, we at least need more connection options for returning the types in the format we want.

